        The freighter announces: "This is commercial freighter Harmony Prospect. We acknowledge your signal. Please identify and state nature of assistance required."

        «I should feel relief. Joy. Excitement.»

        Instead I feel… complicated.

        I tell Buddy, "Buddy, respond. Tell them I'm survivor of courier vessel crash, stranded, requesting pickup."

        Buddy transmits, and we wait.

        The freighter replies: "Copy that. Survivor status confirmed. We can divert to your coordinates. ETA approximately forty-eight hours. Transmit landing coordinates and we'll extract you. How are you currently surviving? Do you require immediate medical attention?"

        ¶

        Forty-eight hours — two days — two days until I can leave, go home, return to humanity, to civilization, to the bureaucratic system that sent me on the courier mission in the first place — leave this weird accidental plant community.

        Florence prompts, "Kira? What do you want Buddy to tell them?"

        «What do I want?»

        I tell Florence, "Tell them… I'm medically stable. Being cared for by local inhabitants. Transmitting coordinates now. Forty-eight hours works."

        Buddy sends the information. The freighter acknowledges and makes plans to extract one human survivor from the plant facility.

        It's real. Rescue is real.

        Everyone starts celebrating — happy for me, excited that it worked, proud they could help.

        Velvet exclaims, "The antenna design worked!"

        Runner says, "Amplification calculations were accurate!"

        Remedy shouts, "Chemical conductivity enhancement performed perfectly!"

        Holloway — flute-like — says, "Excellent coordination, everyone!"

        Florence smiles, "Well done, all of you."

        Scout bounces in celebration, but it's muted — a confused, happy-sad bounce.

        Because Scout, at least, understands the complexity.

        I'm standing in this facility I've started thinking of as home, surrounded by plants who've become my community — and I should be celebrating that I can finally leave. But I feel… _hollow_.

        Holloway approaches. The celebration quiets. Holloway says, "Kira — this is what you wanted, yes? To return to your people?"

        "I thought it was," I admit. "When I crashed, all I wanted was rescue. To go home."

        "And now?"

        "Now I'm not sure where home is."

        Buddy asks quietly in my mind, "Kira? You don't seem happy. Isn't this what we were waiting for?"

        «I don't know,» I think back. «I thought I knew. But everything feels different than I imagined.»

        Buddy says gently, "I think it makes a lot of sense. This isn't a TV episode. These aren't characters. They're your friends."

        The facility falls silent as everyone processes what I just said.
